Part 1 â€“ Fig 2B-C Glycerol contributes to tuberculosis susceptibility in male mice with type 2 diabetes

The assignment is: Better than reproduce the analysis of the experiment presented in Figs. 2B and 2C of the article

Source article: Martinez, Nuria, et al.Â â€œGlycerol contributes to tuberculosis susceptibility in male mice with type 2 diabetes.â€ Nature Communications 14.1 (2023): 5840.

dataset: Martinez-Glycerol-fig2.xlsx

You need to 1) import the data, 2) analyze the data for figures 2B and 2c, and 3) report the results following the example in Section 10.1.1

From the abstract: â€œHere we show that male mice receiving a high-fat diet and streptozotocin to model type 2 diabetes, have higher mortality, more lung pathology, and higher bacterial burden following Mycobacterium tuberculosis infection compared to mice treated with streptozotocin or high-fat diet alone.â€

Results leading up to the experiment in Fig 2: â€œHFD-STZ mice exhibit hypoinsulinemia, insulin resistance, hyperglycemia, and dyslipidemiaâ€ â€“ basically the authors showed that HFD + STZ creates a a type 2 diabetes (T2D) like physiology. The goal is to create a T2D model to see if this T2D physiology is more vulnerable to tuberculosis markers from Mycobacterium tuberculosis infection.

Motivating question: â€œWe hypothesized that the combined perturbation of glucose and lipid metabolism characteristic of type 2 DM, has additive or synergistic effects on TB severity as reported with microvascular complications.â€

Experimental Model Mice infected with Mycobacterium tuberculosis (Mtb)

Authorâ€™s reported result â€œThe infected HFD-STZ mice also had the highest lung CFU and lesion area at 8 weeks p.i. (Fig. 2b, c).â€

Authorâ€™s conclusion 1. â€œOverall, the TB susceptibility phenotype and immune function perturbations in HFD-STZ type 2 DM model identified an additive or synergistic detrimental effect of hyperglyce- mia and altered lipid metabolism on host defense, reminiscent of their combined effect on the vascular complications of type 2 DMâ€ 2. â€œWe speculated that the dyslipidemia associated with type 2 DM could further exacerbate the immunopathy caused by hyperglycemia alone. That notion was reinforced by initial evidence from the present study showing that these combined metabolic perturbations synergistically increased TB severity (Fig. 2)â€

What is Synergy â€“ Google the definition. Also look at the Factorial chapter in the textbook where I discuss synergism.

Response variable: 1. Fig 2b: cfu â€“ bacterial colony forming units 2. Fig 2c: percent_lesion â€“ percent of lung area with TB lesions.

Factor variables

  1. Factor 1: diet with levels = (â€œCDâ€, â€œHFDâ€)
  • CD â€“ control (chow) diet.
  • HFD â€“ high fat diet
  1. Factor 2: stz with levels = (â€œVehâ€, â€œSTZâ€)
  • Veh â€“ â€œvehicleâ€
  • STZ â€“ Streptozotocin

Streptozotocin is a metabolite of the soil microbe Streptomyces achromogenes that damages DNA and is toxic to cells. Remarkably (to me) it is similar enough to glucose that it is transported by GLUT2 (but apparently less so by other GLUTs), which is especially common in pancreatic beta cells, the cells that make insulin. Therefore, STZ kills beta cells and creates diabetes. Because most cell types express little or no GLUT2, it is much less toxic to other cell types. See the wikipedia article for more information.

Groups:

  1. CD/Veh â€“ the negative control giving the background condition
  2. HFD/Veh â€“ A positive control on HFD.
  3. CD/STZ â€“ the positive control on STZ.
  4. HFD/STZ â€“ the focal treatment.

2. Do your own statistics! Do better than the authors!

We can do better using a factorial model! The authors used â€œone-way ANOVAâ€ meaning they â€œflattenedâ€ the 2 x 2 design (two factors each with two groups) into a 1 x 4 (one factor with four groups) model. Tsk-tsk. In the 2 x 2 factorial model, the interaction effect is automatic, because itâ€™s a coefficient of the model. In a flattened analysis, we can still compute the interaction using the manual planned contrasts but GUI packages like Graphpad Prism will not give you the interaction statistics because the software is unaware that itâ€™s a 2 x 2 design if you input it as a 1 x 4 flattened model!

Note that the authors explicitly argued for a synergistic effect. Synergy means â€œmore than the sum of the partsâ€ This is of course a positive interaction! To measure synergy you have to measure the interaction effect!

fig2b_m1 <- lm(cfu ~ diet * stz, data = fig2)
